description: {"blocks":[{"key":"abf77","text":"Below you will find a simple and fast two-step DNA extraction protocol that works well with many different groups of fungi. This protocol can be utilized in preparation for DNA barcoding of fungi utilizing Oxford Nanopore MinION.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"40s1e","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"24qhr","text":"Time required: ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":15}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"3102j","text":"Varies depending on the use case. My samples generally have the metadata and images stored on iNaturalist. For each sample, I go to the iNaturalist observation, validate that the specimen matches the metadata and images, include a unique lab code in the \"Voucher Number(s)\" observational field, record the lab code on the sample packet with a marker, and record the lab code on the associated spreadsheet in the correct cell number. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"15an8","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"blir5","text":"If all of these actions need to be performed, it can take 3-5 hours per 96 samples to load. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4o2hd","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"chtuo","text":"If the iNaturalist observations have already been validated, the lab numbers have been assigned, and all that is required is to put a small amount of tissue in each cell for each sample, then the time outlay can be less than 2 hours per 96 samples.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"55u6v","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5i831","text":"Limitations on Protocol:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":0,"length":24}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"44n4i","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"co77e","text":"There are a number of species groups that will have lower success rates with this protocol. They will either need a more complex DNA extraction protocol that involves grinding, or different primer combinations.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"a9ajc","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7qin1","text":"Low success rates (0-20% of specimens): Cantharellus, Helvella, Strobilomyces, Ophiocordyceps, Panellus","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"55vu6","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5pvps","text":"Moderate success rates (20-60% of specimens): Recalcitrant crusts \u0026 polypores, Cuphophyllus, Neohygrocybe, Tylopilus, Xylaria, Hypoxylaceae, Nidulariaceae","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7b6cn","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2m1hh","text":"Overall, for a mix of general collections, we typically have success rates of 85-95% of specimens. {"blocks":[{"key":"3m2s2","text":"Before starting, I will typically put the specimens in numerical order, which includes adding my own lab/herbarium code to the specimens. This makes the final digital spreadsheet preparation much easier. Having the samples in order allows the final spreadsheet to be populated by drag-and-drop in Excel and it allows all of the iNat numbers to be copy and pasted (always with some minor modification) directly into the final sample spreadsheet. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7k9r0","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9ki72","text":"As an example, I will lay out all of my samples, mark the bags with a lab code (ex - 1 to 96) and enter the same lab code into the iNat Voucher number(s) observational field (Ex - OSF2022-096). I then pull tissue from the samples in that order, filling the cells from right to left across the strip.  (Loading right to left allows the flow to go from A -\u003e H of a typical 96-well plate style format.)","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[{"style":"bold","offset":245,"length":53}],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7c4ef","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6r8eb","text":"  ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"9tvm0","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"lmsa","text":"This process takes some time initially, but it will save time with later with spreadsheet preparation. {"blocks":[{"key":"b3d51","text":"Add a small amount of fungal tissue to each cell. The amount of tissue should be small enough to easily drop to the bottom of the tube. Less is better than more. If you can physically see the sample in the tube it is probably enough for a successful extraction. Remember, you will be filling the tubes with tissue from right to left.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"app0v","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"erfm9","text":"  ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":1}],"data":{}},{"key":"4qmi4","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"fdul9","text":"For dried specimens, I will typically break off a small section of the mushroom with my fingers and place it on a Kimwipe, blank white paper, or on the field data slip in the bag. From there it can be further broken up using tweezers until you spot a piece of the desired size to put in the tube.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ele84","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6olti","text":"For fresh specimens, I will try to pull off the desired amount of tissue for each cell directly from the specimen.  **Note - I no longer use fresh specimens for this protocol. They are more difficult to work with. I will typically dry all specimens before attempting an extraction protocol.**","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"1b14s","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4g4ln","text":"Both dried and fresh specimens use the same visual amount of tissue.
